@node ch_Intro "Introduction"
@next ch_Usage

 Introduction

 APCNames is a program supporting file transfer between Amiga and Macintosh
 without any hardware extension. For the file transfer PC formatted disks are
 used, which can be read by any Amiga with CrossDOS and any Macintosh with
 AccessPC« installed.

 Due to the nature of MS-DOS, file names on PC disks may not be longer than
 eight letters, where file names on the Amiga and the Mac may conist of up to
 31 characters. AccessPC solves this problem by mapping a longer Mac file name
 to a unique PC file name and storing both names into a special file called
 APCINFO.DAT automatically.

 If the disk is inserted into a PC drive, the mapped names and the APCINFO.DAT
 will be shown. If the disk is inserted into a Mac drive again, the original
 files will be shown and the APCINFO.DAT file is invisible.

 An example:

 If on the Mac the file "APCNamesArchive.lha" is written to a PC disk, the 
 disk will contain the following files:

 APCINFO.DAT    <-hidden file created by AccessPC
 APCNAME&.LHA   <-file with truncated name

 What has AccessPC to do with the Amiga ?

 If you have to swap files between Amiga and Macintosh very often (like me)
 and you do not have AMax2 but only Cross-DOS, then you have to transfer
 your files on PC disks (since an Amiga DD drive cannot read the strange Mac
 disks and terms like "data interchange" and "compatibility" are unknown to
 Apple's manager-toy anyway).

 With AccessPC installed the Mac has no troubles with the "8-character
 restriction" of PC file names, but if you insert such a disk into your
 Amiga drive, you will see the same ugly file names like on the PC.

 At this point, APCNames will help you.
@endnode

@node ch_Usage "Using APCNames"
@prev ch_Intro
@next ch_Types

 Using APCNames

 1. File transfer from Mac to Amiga

 If you want to restore the original file names from the Mac on the Amiga,
 you have to copy the contents of the PC disk to an arbitrary Amiga directory
 (also the APCINFO.DAT file !), then to change to it and to run APCNames
 without any arguments. APCNames will then rename the files from the ugly PC
 names to the original Mac names using the APCINFO.DAT file.

 An example:

 * You insert a PC disk into PC0: and see the following contents:

   MYFILE_&.TXT, MYFILE_0.TXT, AMIGATO&.DOC, APCINFO.DAT

 * Copy the 4 files to RAM: and run APCNames from RAM: as follows:

   APCNames

 * Finally you will get following files on RAM:

   Myfile_1.txt, MyFile_2.txt, AmigaToMac.doc.


 2. File transfer from Amiga to Mac

 Also the other direction is possible. If you want to transfer some files
 (with Amiga typical file names) to the Mac, you simply have to run APCNames
 specifying the -c option and the names of your files. It will then do the
 following:

 2.1  renaming the Amiga file names to (ugly) PC file names
 2.2  creating/updating the APCINFO.DAT file

 The renamed files have to be copied to a PC disk together with APCINFO.DAT.
 If you insert the disk into a Mac, it will display your Amiga file names
 again.

 An example:

 * You want to transfer following files to the Mac:

   Myfile_1.txt, MyFile_2.txt, AmigaToMac.doc.

 * Run APCNames as follows:

   APCNames -c Myfile#? *.doc       ;(wildcards also supported)

 * Finally you will get following files, which can be copied to a PC disk:

   MYFILE_&.TXT, MYFILE_0.TXT, AMIGATO&.DOC, APCINFO.DAT


 NOTE: When you insert the PC disk into the Mac drive, by default all files
       transferred from the Amiga won't have a link to a Macintosh
       application, since the @{"type & creator" link ch_Types} IDs generated by APCNames are
       "TEXT" and "????" respectively. Nevertheless APCNames allows you to
       specify type & creator information depending on the file name
       extension. See the next page for more information.

@endnode

@node ch_Types "Types & Creators"
@prev ch_Usage
@next ch_Requir

 Types & Creators

 A useful feature of the Macintosh's Finder is the automatic linkage of a
 document to its creating application ("creator") by means of its embedded
 type & creator information (a crippled imitation of this feature on the
 Amiga is provided by the datatypes.library of OS3.0).

 By default, the type & creator information generated by APCNames allows no
 linkage of the transferred files to a Macintosh application. Finder will 
 display each file as "document" together with a boring icon.

 If you belong to the people who want all transferred files with the
 extension "txt" to become documents of their favourite Mac text editor
 or files with the extension "cc" to become documents of Symantec-C++,
 you can take advantage of the type & creator mapping ability of APCNames.

 1. You create a text file containing specifications like the following ones:

   p        TEXT PJMM
   cc|c|h   TEXT KAHL
   txt      TEXT R*ch
   doc      WDBN MSWD
   ...      TEXT ttxt

 The first string contains one or more file extensions separated by the symbol
 "|". A file name contains a specified file extension if it ends with a period
 followed by the extension (for example "foo.c" and "yy.lex.c" both contain the
 extension "c").
 Furthermore you may use the "..." symbol here to specify type & creator for
 all files not matching the other extensions. If you omit the this
 specification, "TEXT and "????" are used.

 The following two strings specify the type and creator IDs generated for
 each file with the preceding extension(s).

 Furthermore you may intersperse blank lines and one-line comments started by
 "//" into your specification.

 2. Save the specification file to a location you want (for example to "S:"
 as "APCNames.types").

 3. When mapping file names, specify the name of the specification file with
 the "-c" option. An example:

   APCNames -cMyConfigs Tst.c Tst.h

 If "MyConfigs" contains the specifications of the example above, "Tst.c"
 and "Tst.h" become documents of Symantec-C++'s project manager.

 If you have named your file "S:APCNames.types", you may omit the name of the
 specification file, since APCNames will look for this file automatically.

 NOTE: When running APCNames without arguments (mapping from Mac to Amiga),
       there is no usage for the specification file. Only mapping from Amiga
       to Mac is affected.

@endnode

@node ch_Requir "Requirements"
@prev ch_Types
@next ch_Unix

 Requirements

 The binary of APCNames enclosed in this archive needs at least OS 2.04
 (because of the pattern matching functions) to run.

 For all people who want to use APCNames on Unix this version includes also
 a Unix version of APCNames. Since it is written in ANSI-C, it should compile
 with each C compiler (GCC suggested).

 NOTE: If you have to change something in the Unix sources for your OS version,
 please tell me about it. I will consider that change in all future versions
 (if there is any need...).

@endnode

@node ch_Unix "Unix version"
@prev ch_Requir
@next ch_Restr

 Unix version

 If you have don't have anything to do with Macintosh at all but you simply
 want to interchange files between Unix and Amiga via MS-DOS disks, APCNames
 will also help you.

 The unix version of APCNames should compile with GCC properly. It differs
 from the Amiga version in the following points:

 * Since GCC's includes lack definitions of EXIT_FAILURE, SEEK_SET and more,
   I had to add some #defines.

 * Additional "-x" option.
   If your Unix system is equipped with the "MTools" toolkit (consisting of
   mread, mwrite, mdir etc. for handling MS-DOS disks), APCNames will
   additionally act as a file copy program:

   1. Encoding: If you use "-x" with "-c", APCNames will not rename the files
      to be transferred, but write them to the MS-DOS disk with encoded names
      using the "mwrite" utility.

   2. Decoding: If APCNames is run with "-x" only, it will first look after
      the APCINFO.DAT file on the inserted MS-DOS disk. All encoded files
      will then be copied onto your Unix HD using "mread", where they get
      their original (long) file name.

   See also the man page for information on the "-x" option.

@endnode


@node ch_Restr "Restrictions"
@prev ch_Unix
@next ch_Hist

 Restrictions

 APCNames v1.2 only renames files in the current directory. It does not
 process directories recursively.


 Future enhancements (if needed)

 ╗╗APCBrowserźź

 GUI-driven browser for PC0: and PC1: volumes used for file transfer with
 ╗╗APCNamesźź (ß la DiskMaster/DirOpus), providing:

 * control panels for file copy from/to MS-DOS disks
 * MS-DOS files are automatically displayed in their original long names
   (optionally with type/creator), APCINFO.DAT is hidden - full transparence

@endnode

